main event: A white, round object was observed in the sky near Cape Canaveral, Florida in 1952.
interesting points: The object appeared at 35 degrees elevation, was first observed at a distance of 2 to 300 yards, and disappeared at a distance of 5-6 miles.
The object was estimated to be 1,000 feet in altitude and 45-50 feet in diameter, and was observed to be moving at a speed of approximately 1,200 mph.
The object did not have any sound or trail, and the observation of its attitude and distance did not suggest it was a meteor.
A thorough investigation was conducted to eliminate the possibility of the object being a weather balloon, test aircraft, helicopter, or other known phenomenon, but all results were negative.
The only possibility that could not be completely eliminated was that the object was a meteorite, but the description of the object and the observer's estimates made this analysis unlikely.
